-- Australian, New Zealand Stocks: Rio Tinto, Extract, Panoramic, Woodside
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-06-30T06:51:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-30/australian-new-zealand-stocks-bhp-rio-tinto-extract-santos-woodside.html

          
          
             Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index 
declined 1 percent to 4,301.50 at the close of trading in Sydney,
the lowest close since May 25. The index has slipped 12 percent
this quarter after finishing the first quarter little changed
from the end of last year.  
 New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  lost 0.6 percent to 2,972.09 in
Wellington. The index lost 9.1 percent in the last three months,
taking its loss for the first half to 8 percent.  
 The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  
 Mining shares: Copper prices fell the most in five weeks in
New York yesterday after reports signaled a deteriorating
economic outlook in China and the U.S., the world’s top metals
buyers.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
lost 1.2 percent to A$37.65. Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the
world’s third-largest mining company, retreated 2.6 percent to
A$66.66.  
      Extract Resources Ltd.  (EXT AU) advanced 2.4 percent to
A$6.50. The uranium explorer’s stock rating was raised to
“buy” from “hold” at Deutsche Bank AG.  
      Mincor Resources NL  (MCR AU), an Australian nickel producer
that supplies BHP Billiton Ltd., climbed 1.7 percent to A$1.815.
The stock was raised to “hold” from “sell” at Deutsche Bank.  
      Panoramic Resources Ltd.  (PAN AU) rose 3.8 percent to
A$2.18 after the mining company was raised to “buy” from
“hold” at Deutsche Bank.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, slipped 1.7 percent to A$41.84.
Oil dropped for a third day on concern over weakening economic
growth in China and as confidence declined more than forecast
among consumers in the U.S., the world’s biggest energy user.  
